{
  "texts": [
    "Rather than focusing on purely technical features of AI technology, this literature stream considers human-AI collaboration by analyzing different \"features\" of humans (e.g., competencies, knowledge, skill) concerning AI (Anton et al., 2020; Pinski et al., 2023a; Wang et al., 2022).",
    "In contrast to an individual competence or a certain piece of knowledge, AI literacy describes a holistic proficiency with primarily enabling character, as evidenced by the manifold human features (e.g., competencies, knowledge, skill) ascribed to AI literacy (Cetindamar et al., 2022; Dai et al., 2020; Deuze & Beckett, 2022; Hermann, 2021; Long & Magerko, 2020).",
    "Furthermore, AI literacy is distinct from self-efficacy (Bandura, 1986)-a commonly used construct in IS literature-because it describes actual human enablement and capacity to act compared to the human's belief in their capacity to act in an AI context.",
    "In retrospect, technological \"literacy\" is not a new concept (Leidig & Salmela, 2020).",
    "However, due to AI's disruption of core IS assumptions, such as functional transparency or functional consistency (Berente et al., 2021), AI literacy distinguishes itself from other technology literacy concepts, such as digital or data literacy (Eshet-Alkalai, 2004; Kerpedzhiev et al., 2020)."
  ]
}